00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:21.000
[Guest]: Yeah, I know what you mean.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:24.000
[Guest]: There's a slight, like maybe half a second delay,

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:28.000
[Guest]: and sometimes we've spoken over each other just for half a sentence.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.000
[Guest]: I'll do my best to do the same in the studio.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.000
[Amit Varma]: Right. So you made a list of kind of, you know,

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:36.000
[Amit Varma]: the impressions that have stayed with you over a hundred episodes,

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:39.000
[Amit Varma]: or the last 99 episodes of the seen and the unseen.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.000
[Guest]: So first, I must congratulate you.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:42.000
[Guest]: What works, what doesn't work?

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:43.000
[Guest]: Well, I don't know about that.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:46.000
[Guest]: I don't think of these things very critically in terms,

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:48.000
[Guest]: I'm not judging every guest and every person.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
[Guest]: I usually think of it as, you know,

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
[Guest]: some kind of a learning exercise that usually most of your guests

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.000
[Guest]: have an insight that I wouldn't have thought of.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.000
[Guest]: And even if the insight is, you know, very straightforward,

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:03.000
[Guest]: and it's a simple idea,

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:08.000
[Guest]: they bring in a particular amount of context to the area of the world

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.000
[Guest]: that they're speaking about, which I learn a lot from.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:15.000
[Guest]: So I usually think of this in a sort of professorial way

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:17.000
[Guest]: of how do you more critically engage with ideas.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:20.000
[Guest]: I'm not very critical about the guests.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
[Guest]: I'm my favorite guest on your show.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.000
[Guest]: No, I'm kidding. I have a few favorites.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:30.000
[Guest]: I really loved Gunwant Patil. I think he was amazing.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:36.000
[Guest]: What I loved about his show was he has recognized the first principles

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
[Guest]: of liberty and markets, but not the way I did,

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.000
[Guest]: coming from books from Adam Smith and Frederick Hayek

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:45.000
[Guest]: and Frederick Bastiat and so on.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:49.000
[Guest]: It's sort of like farming. He's sort of homegrown, you know.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:53.000
[Guest]: He just, through experience, he's figured out that state coercion

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:56.000
[Guest]: has really led to the misery of farmers.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:59.000
[Guest]: And instead of treating the symptoms the way most of the elites

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:03.000
[Guest]: want to treat just the loans or just the subsidies,

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:07.000
[Guest]: he has really thought about the core problem,

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:10.000
[Guest]: which is that farmers are denied choice.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:14.000
[Guest]: And he was so eloquent about it. He is by far my most favorite guest.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:15.000
[Amit Varma]: No, and you know, it's interesting.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.000
[Amit Varma]: I remember WhatsApping you at the time in great excitement.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:22.000
[Amit Varma]: Our good friend, Barun Mitra, had organized his farmer's conference

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:25.000
[Amit Varma]: in Deolali in Nasik, which had a bunch of these

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:28.000
[Amit Varma]: Shedkari Sangatana leaders who'd worked with Sharad Joshi.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:31.000
[Amit Varma]: And he wanted Bharat to meet India, in his words.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:34.000
[Amit Varma]: So he took a bunch of English-speaking Bombay people along,

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:36.000
[Amit Varma]: me being one of them.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:38.000
[Amit Varma]: And the fascinating thing I realized there was, you know,

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:41.000
[Amit Varma]: I always had the impression, which I now realize to be mistaken,

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:44.000
[Amit Varma]: that our ideas, being so counterintuitive,

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:47.000
[Amit Varma]: will necessarily be the ideas of the elite.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:50.000
[Amit Varma]: And when I got there, I realized that, my God, that, you know,

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:53.000
[Amit Varma]: the way we view the world, many of these farmer leaders,

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.000
[Amit Varma]: like Gunwant Patil ji, Manvendra Kachole ji,

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.000
[Amit Varma]: and a bunch of, you know, really fine, deep thinkers,

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
[Amit Varma]: the way we view the world is pretty common,

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
[Amit Varma]: in the sense we've arrived at the same place, but in different ways.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:06.000
[Amit Varma]: I've arrived at there by finding these ideas in books,

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:10.000
[Amit Varma]: thinking, ha, this makes sense, and then applying them to the real world,

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.000
[Amit Varma]: and over a period of time, they kind of get validated.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:14.000
[Amit Varma]: These guys don't care about the books.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:19.000
[Amit Varma]: These guys have seen, you know, life playing out and affecting them,

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:24.000
[Amit Varma]: and from that, they've come to these, what we would call libertarian conclusions,

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.000
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, they've reached Hayak without reaching Hayak,

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:29.000
[Amit Varma]: they've reached Friedman without reading Friedman,

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:32.000
[Amit Varma]: which is just, which was incredibly fascinating,

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.000
[Amit Varma]: and that was the one Hindi episode I did,

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
[Amit Varma]: because I just wanted him to be comfortable,

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.000
[Guest]: and what did you think of my Hindi?

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:40.000
[Guest]: Your Hindi is terrible.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:41.000
[Unknown]: Okay, don't say that.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:44.000
[Unknown]: I grew up in Delhi, so I have high standards.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:47.000
[Guest]: Gunwan ji's Hindi is excellent.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:48.000
[Unknown]: Obviously.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:49.000
[Guest]: So I really enjoyed that episode.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:51.000
[Guest]: I know for some of your listeners,

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:53.000
[Guest]: the Hindi language bar might have been a bit difficult,

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:56.000
[Guest]: but I was very comfortable listening to him,

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:59.000
[Guest]: and in fact, the thing that both of us picked up on,

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.000
[Guest]: which is that they think of these ideas in a non-academic way,

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:05.000
[Guest]: I think that might be more productive than the way we think about it,

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:08.000
[Guest]: because we think about it in a particular box,

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.000
[Guest]: parts dependent on the literature that we have read,

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:14.000
[Guest]: and then what we have read, we try to apply to the real world

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.000
[Guest]: that we see in front of us.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:19.000
[Guest]: Theirs are just so naturally intuitive and seamless,

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:22.000
[Guest]: I think the way they communicate those ideas

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:26.000
[Guest]: might just be a tad better than what we are trying to do.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
[Amit Varma]: That's the one big thing I got from the episode.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:29.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's pretty mind-blowing also,

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:31.000
[Amit Varma]: because, you know, I got so much feedback after that episode,

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:33.000
[Amit Varma]: saying that, wow, this has completely opened my mind,

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:35.000
[Amit Varma]: I didn't know these were the problems,

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:37.000
[Amit Varma]: and I was thinking that, okay, for like 15 years,

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:40.000
[Amit Varma]: I've been writing columns about exactly these problems,

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:45.000
[Amit Varma]: but yeah, it's completely different when he says it in his voice,

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.000
[Amit Varma]: in his language, and he contextualizes it

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:51.000
[Amit Varma]: in his own personal experience and pain,

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:53.000
[Amit Varma]: and that reaches out and makes a difference.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:55.000
[Guest]: Yeah, and he was a very natural guest,

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:57.000
[Guest]: like all the emotion was right there,

00:08:57.000 --> 00:08:59.000
[Guest]: his frustrations with the government,

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:02.000
[Guest]: his frustrations when he was describing BT cotton,

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
[Guest]: and how he was so thrilled that they did it on the sly,

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.000
[Guest]: and then it became so big that they couldn't quite ban it,

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:11.000
[Guest]: and so he was a very natural sort of,

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:14.000
[Guest]: so I really loved him, I loved Gunwanji.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
[Amit Varma]: That was episode 86, and before you tell me your other favorites,

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:19.000
[Amit Varma]: I got to tell you that your first episode with me

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:20.000
[Amit Varma]: was Right to Property, right?

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:21.000
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
[Amit Varma]: And that was a transitional episode for me,

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.000
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that before that,

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
[Amit Varma]: my impression was I have to hook people onto the show,

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.000
[Amit Varma]: and I'd been told that the data shows

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:33.000
[Amit Varma]: that about 20-minute interviews are the way to go,

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:34.000
[Amit Varma]: and that's your sweet spot,

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.000
[Amit Varma]: and people don't like to listen to more than that,

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
[Amit Varma]: and I used to aim for 20 minutes,

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:40.000
[Amit Varma]: which is mind-blowing to think of it now.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
[Amit Varma]: I even had a 10-minute episode with Mohit Satyanand.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:43.000
[Amit Varma]: I remember.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:46.000
[Amit Varma]: Which is a miniature masterpiece, but it's a miniature.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.000
[Amit Varma]: And then my episode with you on Right to Property

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:50.000
[Amit Varma]: went for an hour, and I thought,

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.000
[Amit Varma]: what a nice conversation this was, you know,

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
[Amit Varma]: and why am I doing 20 minutes?

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And then as I became a regular podcast listener myself,

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:00.000
[Amit Varma]: and started binging on other interview shows like Sam Harris and so on,

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:03.000
[Amit Varma]: I realized that, hey, most people who listen to podcasts regularly

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:05.000
[Amit Varma]: listen at double speed.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:07.000
[Amit Varma]: So if you have a 20-minute show,

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:10.000
[Amit Varma]: by the time you've put on your shoes to go jogging outside,

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:11.000
[Amit Varma]: the 10 minutes are gone.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:12.000
[Amit Varma]: That's double speed.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:13.000
[Amit Varma]: It's all over.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And the kind of podcast I would crave to listen to

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:19.000
[Amit Varma]: would be two-hour conversations, three-hour conversations,

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.000
[Amit Varma]: like Sam Harris sometimes, Joe Rogan,

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:23.000
[Amit Varma]: or Dan Carlin's Great Hardcore History podcast,

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.000
[Amit Varma]: and I thought I need to do more of those,

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:28.000
[Amit Varma]: and we reached a stage where now I aim for a minimum of an hour,

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:31.000
[Amit Varma]: otherwise I feel like it wasn't rewarding enough.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:32.000
[Amit Varma]: And...

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:34.000
[Guest]: My podcast listening habits are similar.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:36.000
[Guest]: So I listen to the podcast on the subway

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.000
[Guest]: when I'm walking the dog or in the car,

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:41.000
[Guest]: and I thought I was the exception,

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.000
[Guest]: that I like really long conversations.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.000
[Guest]: I remember when we did the Right to Property,

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.000
[Guest]: I even said, should we break at some point?

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:49.000
[Guest]: Do we need to re-record something?

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:52.000
[Guest]: And later my husband pointed out to me the same thing that you said,

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:57.000
[Guest]: that it's double speed, and he said traffic is so bad in most places

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:01.000
[Guest]: that it's not like you're getting anywhere from point A to point B in 10 minutes.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:06.000
[Guest]: So most people are stuck in a car or some kind of mass public transit

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:08.000
[Guest]: for at least 40, 45 minutes,

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:13.000
[Guest]: and that seems to be an unexpected boon for podcasters.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:16.000
[Amit Varma]: Traffic is our killer app.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:17.000
[Guest]: Or our friend.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.000
[Amit Varma]: Traffic is our friend.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.000
[Guest]: So what are the other episodes which...

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:25.000
[Guest]: So, you know, I mean, some personally,

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.000
[Guest]: like I think the one you did with Vishwanath,

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.000
[Amit Varma]: the Zen Rain Man episode on...

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Vishwanath Sikandar, yeah.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
[Guest]: Yeah, he was really great.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:36.000
[Guest]: I don't know very much about water conservation in India.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:39.000
[Guest]: I know in general about common pool resource problems, right?

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:41.000
[Guest]: The tragedy of commons that we keep talking about.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:44.000
[Guest]: So the stuff that he spoke about both academically resonated with me

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
[Guest]: and also like I've grown up in India, right?

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:49.000
[Guest]: We've all had the days when your mother said

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.000
[Guest]: take half a bucket of water and you're done.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
[Guest]: So it just resonated with me,

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:57.000
[Guest]: but the types of ideas he talked about, again,

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:00.000
[Guest]: were just so ground up, no pun intended,

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:06.000
[Guest]: and so sort of counterintuitive but very practical.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:10.000
[Guest]: And his general theme that we need to keep it local

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.000
[Guest]: and involve local communities,

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.000
[Guest]: I think that is an underappreciated idea in India.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:18.000
[Guest]: We want Sarkar to do everything

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:21.000
[Guest]: and Sarkar usually means some centralized power.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:26.000
[Guest]: And even in politics, we usually look to who is the prime minister

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:29.000
[Guest]: and not who is your municipal corporator or something like that.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:33.000
[Guest]: So I think that episode really hooked me on.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:35.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, how was the chatting with him?

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:36.000
[Amit Varma]: It was great.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
[Amit Varma]: Our mutual friend Gautam John put me on to him

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
[Amit Varma]: and Gautam said you've got to speak to him

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
[Amit Varma]: and obviously I take Gautam.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:44.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, if Gautam is recommending someone,

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:45.000
[Amit Varma]: then that person is good.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:48.000
[Amit Varma]: So I requested an interview, fixed it up,

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
[Amit Varma]: he got there, I didn't know what to expect.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
[Amit Varma]: So that was one of those episodes which surprised me

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
[Amit Varma]: in the depth of insight that he came up with

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.000
[Amit Varma]: and which surprised a lot of people

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.000
[Amit Varma]: because it's always continuously got great feedback since then.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:01.000
[Amit Varma]: And yeah, that was really good.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, sometimes what happens is that

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.000
[Amit Varma]: you have a guest from whom you expect a lot

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:07.000
[Amit Varma]: and things just don't work out.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:10.000
[Amit Varma]: Maybe sometimes you can't get into that easy conversational flow

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.000
[Amit Varma]: that you crave during a conversation like this

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:13.000
[Amit Varma]: and that doesn't happen

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:15.000
[Amit Varma]: and sometimes they don't open up enough

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:17.000
[Amit Varma]: and the stars don't align.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:18.000
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes you have a guest

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
[Amit Varma]: you have like no expectations from at all

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:23.000
[Guest]: and boom, you end up with something that's kind of soul-marketing.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:26.000
[Guest]: Yeah, he was really, I mean, he was so great.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:27.000
[Guest]: And you know, the simple idea,

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:29.000
[Guest]: we don't think of water that way,

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.000
[Guest]: but water is renewable.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
[Guest]: It replenishes every day.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.000
[Guest]: So the things that he's talking about

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.000
[Guest]: are not even long-term,

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.000
[Guest]: you know, we need to do this over a period of 10 years or 20 years.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
[Guest]: You'll see the results quite quickly.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:44.000
[Guest]: So even from the start of his ideas

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:47.000
[Guest]: to when we get better water resources

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.000
[Guest]: for the local community,

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:50.000
[Guest]: I think it was very valuable.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
[Guest]: I really hope his ideas

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:53.000
[Guest]: get a bigger market

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.000
[Guest]: and can convert into action

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:56.000
[Amit Varma]: in more places.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:57.000
[Amit Varma]: Which is something you were kind of pointing out

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.000
[Amit Varma]: earlier when we were having lunch before this

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:02.000
[Amit Varma]: and you were having phool kopi short shared over Calcutta,

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
[Amit Varma]: which the chef had to make specially for us

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:05.000
[Amit Varma]: because it's off-menu.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:07.000
[Amit Varma]: And you were pointing out that

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:09.000
[Amit Varma]: the episodes which kind of resonated with you

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:11.000
[Amit Varma]: were the ones with that single big idea

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:13.000
[Guest]: which can actually make a difference.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:14.000
[Guest]: Yeah, I really, I mean,

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:16.000
[Guest]: this one I'm biased because Alex Tabarrok

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:19.000
[Guest]: is one of my former professors and a co-author

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:21.000
[Guest]: and, you know, you've met him.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:24.000
[Guest]: He's just one of the most brilliant economists

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:25.000
[Amit Varma]: and insightful people.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:26.000
[Amit Varma]: Such a lovely man, yeah.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Very lovely and generous.

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:28.000
[Guest]: Yes, and also very lovely and generous,

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
[Guest]: but also like just one of the best

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:33.000
[Guest]: insightful economists that I have met.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:35.000
[Guest]: I use his and Tyler Cowen's book

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:37.000
[Guest]: in my principal's class.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
[Guest]: It's full of gems like this.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.000
[Amit Varma]: Your reference was FSI episode.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:42.000
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:43.000
[Guest]: He did two.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:45.000
[Amit Varma]: He did one on rent control and one on FSI.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:46.000
[Guest]: I think rent control,

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.000
[Guest]: we've all been hammering away at it.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:49.000
[Guest]: And if you live in Mumbai,

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:51.000
[Guest]: it's really hard to be a fan of rent control.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:52.000
[Guest]: With the FSI episode,

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.000
[Guest]: what I really loved about it,

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
[Guest]: and this you see in a lot of Alex's work,

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.000
[Guest]: it's, I mean, after all,

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
[Guest]: their site is called Marginal Revolution,

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.000
[Guest]: a small step to change the world, right?

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
[Guest]: So it's a small idea

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:07.000
[Guest]: which could completely change many things.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:10.000
[Guest]: It can change the architecture of Bombay, right?

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:13.000
[Guest]: We live tall instead of live broad, right?

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:15.000
[Guest]: We live in smaller clusters.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:18.000
[Guest]: We think of distance very differently.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
[Guest]: We may start walking to work

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
[Guest]: instead of taking a car to work, right?

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
[Guest]: Prices may drop,

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
[Guest]: so there's more mixed living

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.000
[Guest]: in the sense that, you know,

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
[Guest]: the person who comes to drive my car,

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:33.000
[Guest]: the person who comes to do the housekeeping at home

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:36.000
[Guest]: doesn't have to travel an hour in a local train

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.000
[Guest]: to come and work in our homes

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:39.000
[Guest]: or something like that.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:41.000
[Guest]: So, you know, it becomes more affordable.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.000
[Guest]: And then, you know, cities,

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:46.000
[Guest]: as a landscape, they generate ideas.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
[Guest]: Cities are basically labor markets

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
[Guest]: and they're innovation markets.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:52.000
[Guest]: What kind of ideas can be generated

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.000
[Guest]: if you're not spending all our time

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:57.000
[Guest]: in individual silos and cars on the road

00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:59.000
[Guest]: and instead spending it in communities,

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.000
[Guest]: spending it in public areas,

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:02.000
[Guest]: spending it walking around,

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
[Guest]: spending it listening to podcasts

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:07.000
[Guest]: and in closer proximity with other people?

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:10.000
[Guest]: I think there's also a huge equalizing factor.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
[Guest]: If you look at cities like Hong Kong and New York,

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:17.000
[Guest]: which are tall as opposed to sprawled out,

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:19.000
[Guest]: everyone at every income level

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:21.000
[Guest]: has to interact with each other.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:23.000
[Guest]: I go to the Metropolitan Opera,

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:26.000
[Guest]: which is a fairly elite sort of interest,

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:27.000
[Guest]: even in New York.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.000
[Guest]: And the moment the opera is over,

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:32.000
[Guest]: everyone is walking out to the same subway.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.000
[Guest]: And there is something very lovely about that

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:36.000
[Guest]: in that we genuinely,

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.000
[Guest]: despite our income and class differences,

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
[Guest]: we can genuinely interact with each other,

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:42.000
[Guest]: make eye contact

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.000
[Guest]: when we're in the same subway compartment

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:45.000
[Guest]: and things like that.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:47.000
[Guest]: So a simple thing like changing the FSI

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:50.000
[Guest]: can have very long-term consequences

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:53.000
[Guest]: on the kind of spontaneous order

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
[Amit Varma]: that emerges for the lack of a better word.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:56.000
[Amit Varma]: I'll just sum it up for my listeners

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
[Amit Varma]: by saying FSI basically is how tall

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
[Amit Varma]: you're allowed to make your buildings.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:03.000
[Amit Varma]: And Bombay has a very low FSI of around 1.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.000
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of cities around the world

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:07.000
[Amit Varma]: have FSIs of 15, 25, 30, and so on,

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:09.000
[Amit Varma]: like New York and Hong Kong.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.000
[Amit Varma]: And Alex's point can be summed up

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:12.000
[Amit Varma]: in just three words.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:14.000
[Amit Varma]: Reclaim the sky.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:15.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, we are restricted

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:17.000
[Amit Varma]: by how much land we have access to.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:19.000
[Amit Varma]: Don't think of reclaiming the sea

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:20.000
[Amit Varma]: or reclaiming land.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Reclaim the sky.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:23.000
[Amit Varma]: Just build upwards.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.000
[Amit Varma]: And all the typical objections fall apart,

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:27.000
[Amit Varma]: which he sort of addresses

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:29.000
[Amit Varma]: in that great episode,

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:31.000
[Amit Varma]: which was one of the early 20-minute episodes.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:32.000
[Amit Varma]: And now I look back on that

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:34.000
[Amit Varma]: and I'm thinking that, damn it,

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:36.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, Alex Tabarrok came with me

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:38.000
[Amit Varma]: and sat where you are sitting twice.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:40.000
[Amit Varma]: And I spoke to him for 20 minutes each.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:41.000
[Guest]: What a waste.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm sure he'll give you more time.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:46.000
[Guest]: He's an incredibly lovely and generous person.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.000
[Guest]: So the FSI was one of those ideas.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:50.000
[Guest]: You know, another one of them

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.000
[Guest]: was the television price controls episode

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.000
[Amit Varma]: that you did with Ashok Malik.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
[Guest]: And, you know, we all complain

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
[Guest]: about how terrible television is.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.000
[Guest]: Like, it just caters to the lowest common denominator.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:03.000
[Guest]: We all complain about how terrible

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:05.000
[Guest]: news channels are, right, on TV.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:08.000
[Guest]: And it's just this screaming match

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:11.000
[Guest]: with even the screen,

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:12.000
[Guest]: the amount of information

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.000
[Guest]: and the number of tickers going on.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:15.000
[Guest]: It's like my stress levels increase

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:17.000
[Guest]: the moment I watch television.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:19.000
[Guest]: And the quality is pretty poor.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:20.000
[Guest]: There is no real analysis.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:21.000
[Guest]: There's no insight.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.000
[Guest]: It's a screaming match.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:25.000
[Guest]: There's a lot of misrepresentation of facts.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:28.000
[Guest]: And Ashok Malik basically told us

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.000
[Guest]: that it's not cultural.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:33.000
[Guest]: It's a problem of licensing and price controls.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:36.000
[Guest]: And the same way it produces poor quality food

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
[Guest]: or poor quality apartments in Mumbai,

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
[Guest]: it is producing poor quality television.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.000
[Amit Varma]: And Ashok's point fundamentally to sum it up

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.000
[Amit Varma]: was that, look, it's very easy to blame

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:45.000
[Amit Varma]: private operators, right?

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:46.000
[Amit Varma]: Hey, television is so bad.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:47.000
[Amit Varma]: It's not the state's fault.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:48.000
[Amit Varma]: But actually what happens...

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:49.000
[Amit Varma]: See, my Hindi is so good.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:52.000
[Amit Varma]: But actually what happens is that

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
[Amit Varma]: the state carries out price controls

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:57.000
[Amit Varma]: in terms of they have sold these licenses

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:59.000
[Amit Varma]: at such exorbitant amounts

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:02.000
[Amit Varma]: and therefore stopped people coming into the market

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
[Amit Varma]: that the guys who've paid so much money

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.000
[Amit Varma]: for these licenses have no option

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:08.000
[Amit Varma]: but to cater to the lowest common denominator,

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.000
[Amit Varma]: which is why you'll see Arnab

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.000
[Amit Varma]: and variations of Arnab on all the news channels.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:13.000
[Amit Varma]: It's a screaming match.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And you don't have space for cultivating niches

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:17.000
[Amit Varma]: or going into nuance.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:19.000
[Amit Varma]: Or subscription television.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, because once you pay that kind of money,

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:22.000
[Amit Varma]: you don't have a choice.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:24.000
[Amit Varma]: It's a structural problem created by the state.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:27.000
[Amit Varma]: So don't blame your bad television on Republic TV.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.000
[Amit Varma]: Republic TV is a symptom.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:31.000
[Guest]: I think that's...

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
[Guest]: Another symptom is that you're listening to this

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.000
[Unknown]: as a podcast and not on radio.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.000
[Guest]: This could be a lovely radio show,

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:39.000
[Guest]: but radio stations only want to play Bollywood music

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:41.000
[Guest]: because, again, that's the largest market

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:42.000
[Guest]: that you can have.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's the point Amit Doshi actually keeps making,

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:46.000
[Amit Varma]: where he says that if you look at New York,

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:48.000
[Guest]: you have so many dozens of FM stations.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:49.000
[Guest]: Excellent radio.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:50.000
[Amit Varma]: Because it's cheap.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:51.000
[Amit Varma]: So you can cater to every niche,

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:52.000
[Amit Varma]: you can cater to every taste,

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:53.000
[Amit Varma]: you can experiment.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:55.000
[Amit Varma]: Over here, you have a few licenses sold

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:56.000
[Amit Varma]: for many whatever it is,

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:57.000
[Amit Varma]: tens, hundreds of crores.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:19:58.000
[Amit Varma]: You have to recover that money.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:19:59.000
[Amit Varma]: You have no option.

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:00.000
[Amit Varma]: You have to go lowest common.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:01.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:03.000
[Guest]: And the lowest common here is,

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:05.000
[Guest]: you know, jokes and Bollywood.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:06.000
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.000
[Guest]: With a few traffic updates thrown in

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:09.000
[Guest]: or sprinkled in, right?

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:11.000
[Guest]: And it's the same old, same old, right?

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:12.000
[Guest]: The Gabbar's voice.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.000
[Guest]: And yesterday I was thinking,

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:16.000
[Guest]: the number of RD Burman riffs,

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:17.000
[Guest]: like we don't even have new music

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:18.000
[Guest]: on these radio shows, right?

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:20.000
[Guest]: The number of times like some RD Burman riffs

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:21.000
[Guest]: plays on radio,

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:23.000
[Guest]: this is all because that is what is

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:25.000
[Guest]: instantly recognizable.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:27.000
[Guest]: You're sitting in the car most of the times

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:28.000
[Guest]: when you're listening to the radio.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.000
[Guest]: And you want people to tune in,

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:32.000
[Guest]: which means they have to have

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:33.000
[Guest]: either celebrity interviews

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:34.000
[Guest]: or something like this.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:38.000
[Guest]: And your show could be wonderful on radio.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:40.000
[Guest]: Like it could get this fantastic market

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:43.000
[Guest]: if it could be broadcast over radio waves,

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:45.000
[Guest]: but it simply cannot be done.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:46.000
[Guest]: And the problem is exactly the same

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:49.000
[Guest]: as what Ashok Malik discussed with television.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:51.000
[Amit Varma]: I actually think it's better this way

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:52.000
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that,

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:53.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, the future of television,

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:54.000
[Amit Varma]: for example,

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:55.000
[Amit Varma]: is not appointment viewing,

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:56.000
[Amit Varma]: it's streaming,

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:57.000
[Amit Varma]: it's on-demand viewing.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:20:58.000
[Amit Varma]: And similarly,

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:02.000
[Amit Varma]: so what Netflix is to Star Plus,

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:05.000
[Amit Varma]: I would say that IBM podcasts

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:07.000
[Amit Varma]: or podcasts in general

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:08.000
[Amit Varma]: are to FM radio.

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:10.000
[Guest]: Fair enough, but I'm an economist.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:11.000
[Guest]: All cost is opportunity cost.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:13.000
[Guest]: You could have been a radio show host

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:14.000
[Guest]: 15 years ago,

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:16.000
[Guest]: and we could have had a huge market

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:18.000
[Guest]: of people who are educated in policy.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:19.000
[Guest]: Which never happened.

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:20.000
[Guest]: And not just you,

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.000
[Guest]: there could have been multiple variations

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:23.000
[Unknown]: of this kind of show,

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:24.000
[Guest]: which never happened.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:26.000
[Guest]: And we had to wait for one,

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:30.000
[Guest]: technology to help us decentralize the medium.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:31.000
[Guest]: And two,

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:33.000
[Guest]: we had to wait for something like Jio,

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:35.000
[Guest]: which has put data on every phone.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:36.000
[Guest]: Otherwise it would have only been

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:38.000
[Guest]: a rich man's play thing, right?

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Cell phone and data connection.

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:41.000
[Amit Varma]: And I could actually have made some money.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:43.000
[Guest]: And you could have made some money.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:45.000
[Guest]: I did offer to buy lunch.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:47.000
[Amit Varma]: You did offer to buy lunch

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:48.000
[Amit Varma]: but we cannot have our guests

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:49.000
[Amit Varma]: buying our host lunch.

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:51.000
[Guest]: We are very feminist on this show.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:54.000
[Guest]: So we also offer to buy lunch.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:55.000
[Amit Varma]: You offered,

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:56.000
[Amit Varma]: but the offer was declined.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:58.000
[Amit Varma]: When I come to New York next,

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:00.000
[Amit Varma]: perhaps as a starving refugee,

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:01.000
[Amit Varma]: you can buy me a meal at the time.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.000
[Guest]: I don't think Trump's government

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:05.000
[Unknown]: is taking in refugees.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:08.000
[Guest]: You might be able to come in as a podcaster.

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:10.000
[Guest]: You might have better luck with that.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:11.000
[Amit Varma]: Starving podcaster.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:13.000
[Amit Varma]: Make podcasting great again.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:15.000
[Guest]: Then a couple of other episodes.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:18.000
[Guest]: Since you mentioned starving podcaster,

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:21.000
[Guest]: one idea which I think can have a big impact

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:23.000
[Guest]: is the dhanwapsi idea

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:25.000
[Guest]: that Rajesh Jain talked about, right?

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:27.000
[Guest]: I mean, the idea is pretty simple.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:30.000
[Guest]: It is a direct transfer of public wealth,

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:33.000
[Guest]: but we keep saying this is our wealth.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:34.000
[Guest]: These are public sources,

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:37.000
[Guest]: but they are not controlled by us.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:39.000
[Guest]: They're controlled by representation of us,

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:40.000
[Guest]: which is the government.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:42.000
[Guest]: So they really become the play thing

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:45.000
[Guest]: of those few people in power,

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:47.000
[Guest]: whether it is Indian forests,

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:50.000
[Guest]: Indian mines, Indian roads, Indian land.

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:52.000
[Guest]: I mean, we're in Mumbai.

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:55.000
[Guest]: Half of the town part of Mumbai,

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:56.000
[Guest]: the southern part of Mumbai,

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:58.000
[Guest]: is state land, right?

00:22:58.000 --> 00:22:59.000
[Guest]: Whether it's the port

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:01.000
[Guest]: or whether it's all these LIC buildings

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:03.000
[Guest]: and all these old buildings.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:05.000
[Guest]: And that's a lot of locked up value

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:08.000
[Guest]: which the state has no business holding on to.

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:10.000
[Guest]: And Rajesh Jain's simple idea is

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:14.000
[Guest]: we need the state to divest this wealth

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:16.000
[Guest]: and put it in a fund

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:18.000
[Guest]: and transfer it one time

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:20.000
[Guest]: to every single family in India.

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:21.000
[Guest]: And it has to be equal.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:23.000
[Guest]: It has to be non-discriminatory.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:25.000
[Guest]: And it is really the people's wealth

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:28.000
[Guest]: and people will know how to spend it better.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:29.000
[Amit Varma]: Right?

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:30.000
[Amit Varma]: That was an interesting episode in the sense

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:32.000
[Amit Varma]: my episode with Rajesh was two hours long.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:33.000
[Amit Varma]: My longest so far,

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:34.000
[Amit Varma]: but hopefully I'll have many more

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:35.000
[Amit Varma]: which are much longer.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:37.000
[Amit Varma]: But that was two hours long

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:39.000
[Amit Varma]: and everybody said it was too short.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:40.000
[Amit Varma]: I wanted more of it,

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:41.000
[Amit Varma]: which is uniformly.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:42.000
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is, you know,

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:43.000
[Amit Varma]: like I've told Rajesh

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:44.000
[Amit Varma]: and if he's listening to this,

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:45.000
[Amit Varma]: I know he won't mind my saying it,

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:47.000
[Amit Varma]: but I don't really think

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:49.000
[Amit Varma]: his specific short-term plans

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:50.000
[Amit Varma]: or what he's doing with Dhanwapsya

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:51.000
[Amit Varma]: are going to work at all.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:53.000
[Amit Varma]: It's like almost a fool's dream.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:56.000
[Amit Varma]: But where I appreciate what he's...

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:58.000
[Amit Varma]: I used it as a phrase,

00:23:58.000 --> 00:23:59.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm not calling him a fool.

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:00.000
[Amit Varma]: Far from that.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:03.000
[Amit Varma]: But what is important about the venture,

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:04.000
[Amit Varma]: nevertheless,

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:07.000
[Amit Varma]: is to make that conceptual breakthrough.

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:09.000
[Amit Varma]: Because most people just think

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:10.000
[Amit Varma]: that all the wealth that they have

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:12.000
[Amit Varma]: is the wealth that they have, you know.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:13.000
[Amit Varma]: If they're poor, they're poor.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:16.000
[Amit Varma]: But what Rajesh is trying to get across to you

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:17.000
[Amit Varma]: is that, look,

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:18.000
[Amit Varma]: our public wealth is so much

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:20.000
[Amit Varma]: that every individual is actually worth,

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:21.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, 50 lakhs

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:23.000
[Amit Varma]: or even more than that.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:25.000
[Amit Varma]: And all of that is being wasted.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:27.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's time to give some of it

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:28.000
[Amit Varma]: back to the people

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:29.000
[Amit Varma]: instead of just lying around.

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Especially in a poor country like ours,

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:31.000
[Amit Varma]: where, you know,

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:32.000
[Amit Varma]: poverty is still a problem

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:35.000
[Amit Varma]: we are trying to tackle 71 years later.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:37.000
[Amit Varma]: So just conceptually in terms of

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:38.000
[Amit Varma]: realizing that the government

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:40.000
[Amit Varma]: is not a separate, mybop entity

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:41.000
[Amit Varma]: and what it has is what it has.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:42.000
[Amit Varma]: Realizing that, no,

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:44.000
[Amit Varma]: the government is your servant

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:46.000
[Amit Varma]: and what we call public wealth

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:47.000
[Amit Varma]: is actually our wealth.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:49.000
[Amit Varma]: It's our debt capital, so to say.

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:50.000
[Guest]: No, I'm with you on that.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:53.000
[Guest]: I am in the business of ideas

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:54.000
[Guest]: and not so much implementation.

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:56.000
[Guest]: So I think about it

00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:58.000
[Guest]: in terms of the value of ideas

00:24:58.000 --> 00:24:59.000
[Guest]: and not how quickly

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:02.000
[Guest]: this can turn into action necessarily.

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:03.000
[Guest]: And there are ideas

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:05.000
[Guest]: for whom the time may not have come yet,

00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:07.000
[Guest]: which are not popular enough.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:08.000
[Guest]: But nevertheless,

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:09.000
[Guest]: I think this is something

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:10.000
[Guest]: worth thinking about.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:11.000
[Guest]: And even if Dhan Vapasi

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:13.000
[Guest]: by itself doesn't happen,

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:15.000
[Guest]: the change in mindset

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:17.000
[Guest]: that this is our wealth,

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:19.000
[Guest]: they simply control it

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:21.000
[Guest]: and we need to take back the control,

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:23.000
[Guest]: I think that idea is very powerful.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:24.000
[Guest]: Right?

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:26.000
[Guest]: Whether we redistribute 15 lakhs

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:27.000
[Guest]: or 50 lakhs

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:28.000
[Guest]: or whatever the number is

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:29.000
[Guest]: or how it is done

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:30.000
[Guest]: and whether it's an entitlement

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:31.000
[Guest]: or a transfer,

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:33.000
[Guest]: those are things, you know,

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:34.000
[Guest]: which are less interesting.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:35.000
[Guest]: But I think that a simple idea

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:37.000
[Guest]: is so powerful

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:39.000
[Guest]: that this is really our wealth

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:40.000
[Guest]: and it must be returned

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:41.000
[Guest]: to us in some way.

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:43.000
[Guest]: It's been taken away from us.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:44.000
[Guest]: I don't think Indians

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:45.000
[Guest]: think that way.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:46.000
[Guest]: Right?

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.000
[Guest]: It's usually government's wealth

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:49.000
[Guest]: and we are clearly

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:51.000
[Guest]: not participants in the government

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:52.000
[Guest]: because they only think

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:55.000
[Guest]: of citizens come elections.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:57.000
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:25:58.000
[Guest]: Another big idea, I think,

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.000
[Guest]: which has a huge impact

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:01.000
[Guest]: and India really needs

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:02.000
[Guest]: is the episode that you did

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:03.000
[Guest]: with Parth Shah.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:06.000
[Guest]: He's another old friend,

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:07.000
[Guest]: a common friend of ours

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:10.000
[Guest]: and I think what Parth is doing

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:11.000
[Guest]: with the right to education

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:12.000
[Guest]: and school choice

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:13.000
[Guest]: is extremely valuable

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:17.000
[Guest]: and I think the two-fold idea,

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:18.000
[Guest]: you know,

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:19.000
[Guest]: one that the right to education

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:21.000
[Guest]: is simply driving out

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:23.000
[Guest]: the private market

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:25.000
[Guest]: because it's trying to...

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:26.000
[Guest]: The Right to Education Act

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:28.000
[Guest]: essentially defines

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:30.000
[Guest]: all education goods as inputs.

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:31.000
[Guest]: Right?

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:32.000
[Guest]: What is a good school?

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:33.000
[Guest]: A good school is one

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:34.000
[Guest]: which has a playground,

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:35.000
[Guest]: which has bathrooms,

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:36.000
[Guest]: which has windows of this size

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:38.000
[Guest]: and which has a midday meal

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:39.000
[Guest]: and, you know,

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:40.000
[Guest]: so on and so forth.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:41.000
[Guest]: According to me,

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:42.000
[Guest]: a good school is one

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:43.000
[Guest]: where the children learn

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:44.000
[Unknown]: and I have read

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:45.000
[Guest]: the Right to Education Act

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:46.000
[Guest]: and there's not a single

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:48.000
[Guest]: learning outcome mentioned

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:49.000
[Guest]: in the schedule.

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:50.000
[Guest]: Right?

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:51.000
[Guest]: So this mindset

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:53.000
[Guest]: that you can have a good school

00:26:53.000 --> 00:26:55.000
[Guest]: only if it checks off

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:56.000
[Guest]: all these boxes

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:57.000
[Guest]: and it looks like a good school.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:26:58.000
[Guest]: Right?

00:26:58.000 --> 00:26:59.000
[Guest]: And this is, again,

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:00.000
[Guest]: typically a problem

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:01.000
[Guest]: of elites making policy.

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:02.000
[Guest]: They go to Norway or Sweden

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:03.000
[Guest]: or wherever

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:04.000
[Guest]: and see what good schools look like

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:06.000
[Guest]: and then they turn it into policy.

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:07.000
[Guest]: The trouble is

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:09.000
[Guest]: a lot of great learning takes place

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:11.000
[Guest]: in tiny budget schools

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:12.000
[Guest]: which cannot afford

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:14.000
[Guest]: windows sometimes,

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:15.000
[Guest]: which cannot afford,

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:16.000
[Guest]: you know,

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:17.000
[Guest]: a good teacher-student ratio

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:18.000
[Guest]: or cannot afford

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:21.000
[Guest]: a good student-to-bathroom ratio

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:22.000
[Guest]: and so on and so forth.

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:24.000
[Guest]: And they are providing

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:25.000
[Guest]: a better service.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:26.000
[Guest]: We know that for a fact

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:27.000
[Guest]: because poor parents

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:29.000
[Guest]: are willing to pay

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:30.000
[Guest]: a few thousand rupees

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:31.000
[Guest]: in these budget private schools

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:32.000
[Guest]: rather than send their children

